3.ln -sCreate symbolic link (shortcut) for a file

ln -s Mathews.txt Mathews


4.lnCreate hard link for a file

ln Mathews.txt Matson


5.statDisplay time stamp of the file

stat Mathews.txt


6.touch  Change the time stamp of the file


touch -t 202312310100 Mathews.txt



7.touch  Create empty file


touch johnathan


8.tailPrint all lines in a file from fifth line onwards


tail -n +5 Mathews.txt



9.init 0, poweroffShutdown (Only for super-user)


sudo poweroff




10.init 6, rebootReboot (Only for super-user)

sudo reboot



12.whoamiFind current user


whoami



13.ttyFind current terminal


tty


14.who am iFind current user and terminal


whoami



15.usersFind all users logged into the system



users


16.whoFind all users logged in and terminals in use



who





17.grep, egrep, fgrepFind a given word/pattern from the file

grep m222 Mathews.txt

m222 Bartunga chirimiri




18.chmodMake a file as read-only

chmod u-w Mathews.txt
chmod 740 Mathews.txt


chmod 400 Mathews.txt

john@john-VivoBook-15-ASUS-Laptop-X507UAR:~/Desktop/Home_Practice$ ls -l Mathews.txt
-r-------- 2 john john 87 Dec 21 15:22 Mathews.txt


19.chmodMake a file as write, read and execute



chmod u=rwx Mathews.txt
john@john-VivoBook-15-ASUS-Laptop-X507UAR:~/Desktop/Home_Practice$ ls -l Mathews.txt
-rwx------ 2 john john 87 Dec 21 15:22 Mathews.txt





20.wc (using redirection)Take input from the file, count words and store output to other file


wc Mathews.txt
 6 13 87 Mathews.txt



21.who | wc (using pipe)Count words in output of “who” command


who | wc



22.head, tail (using pipe)Print lines 5 to 10 from the given file


head -n +5 Mathews.txt | tail -n +4
ISRO
NASA




23.sort , uniq (using pipe)Print the uniq values from the unsorted file


sort Mathews.txt | uniq




24.who, grep (using pipe)Display all users not using tty2, tty3, tty4







25.lsDisplay all files in ascending order of their file size



ls -lths



26.ls, grep (using pipe)Count number of files and directories from current directory


ls -l | grep "^-" | wc -l



27.ls, grep (using pipe)Display only hidden files in a directory


ls -al | grep "^-" | wc -l



28.trConvert file contents into uppercase , also learn "-s" option of this command



tr -s "[:lower:]" "[:upper:]" <Mathews.txt> Mat.txt
john@john-VivoBook-15-ASUS-Laptop-X507UAR:~/Desktop/Home_Practice$ cat Mat.txt
JOHN MATHEWS
M222 BARTUNGA CHIRIMIRI
INDIA TEAM
ISRO
NASA
NASA
CHELSEA AND MACHESTER UNITED




29.cutSplit the file contents using delimiter and print required fields



cut -d ' ' -f 1,4 Mathews.txt
john
m222
india
ISRO
NASA
NASA
Chelsea UNited









